Heuristics to detect slow mixing chains

Key idea: run several independent chains from ‚Äúover-dispersed‚Äù initializations.

Over-dispersed: use at least as much noise as the prior (roughly).

Check for differences between the independent chains:

Trace plots.
Rank plots.

These are not bullet-proof methods‚Ä¶
‚Ä¶ but it is still a good idea to use them unless theory provides guarantees (e.g.¬†log-concave distributions).


Example of fast and slow mixing chains

suppressPackageStartupMessages(require(rstan))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(require(ggplot2))
suppressPackageStartupMessages(require(bayesplot))

Easy problem: a familiar beta-binomial problem.

data {
  int&lt;lower=0&gt; n_trials;
  int&lt;lower=0&gt; n_successes;
}
parameters {
  real&lt;lower=0, upper=1&gt; p;
}

model {
  p ~ uniform(0, 1);
  n_successes ~ binomial(n_trials, p);
}

Challenging problem: binomial likelihood, but with ‚Äútoo many parameters.‚Äù

Write \(p = p_1 p_2\), where \(p_i \sim {\mathrm{Unif}}(0, 1)\).
This creates an unidentifiability: for each value \(p\) there are several possible \(p_1, p_2\) such that \(p = p_1 p_2\).
The posterior looks like a ‚Äúthin ridge‚Äù (see visualization here, obtained using tempering, covered in week 12).





data {
  int&lt;lower=0&gt; n_trials;
  int&lt;lower=0&gt; n_successes;
}
parameters {
  real&lt;lower=0, upper=1&gt; p1;
  real&lt;lower=0, upper=1&gt; p2;
}

model {
  p1 ~ uniform(0, 1);
  p2 ~ uniform(0, 1);
  n_successes ~ binomial(n_trials, p1 * p2);
}


We run both easy and hard problems with 2 parallel chains each.
In practice use more than 2.


fit_easy = sampling(
  betabinom,
  seed = 1,
  chains = 2,
  refresh = 0,
  data = list(n_trials=10000000, n_successes=10000000/2),       
  iter = 1000                   
)

fit_hard = sampling(
  unid,
  seed = 1,
  chains = 2,
  refresh = 0,
  data = list(n_trials=10000000, n_successes=10000000/2),       
  iter = 1000                   
)

Trace plots: spot the difference between the easy and hard problems (each line in a given plot is an independent chain).

mcmc_trace(fit_easy, pars = c("p")) + theme_minimal()







mcmc_trace(fit_hard, pars = c("p1")) + theme_minimal()








